The Principal Investigator's research lies in the field of arithmetic geometry, which lies at the intersection of number theory and geometry.  At its core, the theory uses geometric methods to study integer or rational solutions to systems of polynomial equations.  The particular kinds of equations studied by the PI define geometric objects called Shimura varieties. 



It was first noticed in the 1970's that in the special case of a two-dimensional Shimura variety (a Shimura surface), one could find a family of smaller Shimura curves whose intersections with one another could be explicitly computed.  These intersection multiplicities then turned out to be numbers appearing in different branches of mathematics, especially in the representation theory of groups and the theory of modular forms.

The PI has found many new such examples of this phenomenon, in which the Shimura surface and its family of embedded curves are replaced by higher dimensional analogues, and the intersection multiplicities are closely related to quantities appearing in other branches of mathematics.  By exploiting such relations, the PI and his coauthors have done the following:

 (1)  proved new cases of a long-standing conjecture expressing certain integrals on higher-dimensional tori (period integrals) as infinite products (Artin L-functions);

(2)  determined the structure of the reduction modulo different primes of the supersingular loci of Shimura varieties associate to orthogonal groups;

(3)  proved new relations between the intersections of cycles on moduli spaces of Shtukas and higher derivatives of automorphic L-functions;

(4)  shown that certain formal generating series of cycles on unitary and orthogonal Shimura varieties are modular forms.

Aspects of these projects were the basis of the doctoral theses of three Ph.D. students at Boston College, and one project was joint with a postdoctoral researcher under the PI?s supervision.





